From: 4noha
Subject: dwmmc: replace partial pwrseq with full power cycle on DVACT_RESUME
License: ISC (this patch modifies OpenBSD source and inherits ISC; see ../LICENSE-ISC)

dwmmc: replace partial pwrseq with full power cycle on DVACT_RESUME.

Problem (2026-06-05, DM250 / rk3128):
  After resume, bwfm0 (WiFi) never re-attaches even when the host
  kernel completes suspend/resume cleanly (no crash, no error 60). The
  persistent harness log from the v3-diag kernel showed the exact
  failure point via numbered printfs in if_bwfm_sdio.c (see
  bwfm-attach-diag.diff):

    BWFMD A1 activate DVACT_QUIESCE if_flags=0x8843 ic_state=4
    BWFMD A2 activate DVACT_WAKEUP
    BWFMD D1 detach entry flags=1
    BWFMD 01 match entry        <- only ONCE; at boot it fires twice
                                    (function 1 + function 2)
    <no BWFMD 10 attach entry>

  bwfm_sdio_match (if_bwfm_sdio.c) rejects the re-attach because
  sf->sc->sc_function_count == 1 — the chip reported only ONE SDIO
  function via CMD5 instead of the expected two.

Root cause:
  dwmmc-resume-pwrseq.diff fixed the original error 60 (chip totally
  unresponsive after resume) by explicitly calling dwmmc_pwrseq_pre /
  post from DVACT_RESUME. But pwrseq alone only toggles the WL_REG_ON
  / reset-gpios line; it does NOT cycle the vmmc regulator. Meanwhile
  dwmmc_bus_power() — the only path that performs both the regulator
  enable AND the pwrseq pre/post pair that a cold boot uses — gates
  its work on sc_vdd transitioning from 0 to >0, and sc_vdd still
  holds the pre-suspend voltage after resume. When the sdmmc layer's
  force-detach + re-discover path calls bus_power(3.3V) it sees vdd
  unchanged, skips both the regulator cycle and the pwrseq, and leaves
  the chip in the partial state that pwrseq alone produced.

  In that partial state AP6212A responds to CMD5 with only 1 SDIO
  function (function 1, WLAN) instead of 2 (WLAN + BT mailbox).
  sdmmc_io_scan() allocates a single sdmmc_function entry,
  bwfm_sdio_match returns 0 at
      if (sf->sc->sc_function_count <= 1) return 0;
  and bwfm_sdio_attach is never called — bwfm0 ifnet is gone for the
  rest of the boot.

Fix:
  Stop calling pwrseq explicitly from DVACT_RESUME. Instead, drop the
  vmmc regulator refcount and zero sc_vdd so the next bus_power() call
  from sdmmc_card_attach() -> sdmmc_enable() sees a real "0 -> 3.3V"
  transition and runs the full
      regulator_enable + pwrseq_pre + pwrseq_post
  sequence that cold boot uses. The chip then re-enumerates both SDIO
  functions correctly and bwfm_sdio_match accepts the re-attach.

  This subsumes dwmmc-resume-pwrseq.diff (the prior step): the new path
  runs pwrseq via the same code that cold boot exercises, so we get
  pwrseq AND the regulator cycle pwrseq alone was missing.

Target: sys/dev/fdt/dwmmc.c::dwmmc_activate()
Depends: bwfm_sdio_activate (bwfm-suspend-down.diff v3) takes net80211
  down on QUIESCE, so the in-flight detach during resume is safe.
Supersedes: dwmmc-resume-pwrseq.diff (rolled into this patch).

--- sys/dev/fdt/dwmmc.c.orig
+++ sys/dev/fdt/dwmmc.c
@@ dwmmc_activate(struct device *self, int act) @@
 	switch (act) {
 	case DVACT_RESUME:
 		/* dwmmc_host_reset will clobber these */
 		bus_width = sc->sc_bus_width;
 		bus_freq = sc->sc_bus_freq;
 		bus_timing = sc->sc_bus_timing;

 		clock_enable_all(sc->sc_node);
 		reset_deassert_all(sc->sc_node);
-		if (sc->sc_pwrseq) {
-			dwmmc_pwrseq_pre(sc->sc_pwrseq);
-			dwmmc_pwrseq_post(sc->sc_pwrseq);
-		}
+
+		/*
+		 * Force a full boot-style power cycle on the SDIO card so it
+		 * re-enumerates all functions correctly after resume. Dropping
+		 * the regulator refcount and zeroing sc_vdd makes the next
+		 * dwmmc_bus_power() (called from the sdmmc re-discover path
+		 * after the force-detach) see a 0 -> on transition, which is
+		 * the only path that runs both regulator_enable AND pwrseq
+		 * pre/post. Without this, calling pwrseq alone here brings the
+		 * chip up only partially: SDIO CMD5 then reports a single
+		 * function on AP6212A and bwfm_sdio_match() rejects the
+		 * re-attach because it requires sc_function_count > 1.
+		 *
+		 * Replaces the explicit pwrseq from dwmmc-resume-pwrseq.diff
+		 * (which only solved error 60 but introduced this partial-init
+		 * problem). The re-attach path now exercises the same code as
+		 * cold boot.
+		 */
+		if (sc->sc_vdd > 0 && sc->sc_vmmc)
+			regulator_disable(sc->sc_vmmc);
+		sc->sc_vdd = 0;
+
 		dwmmc_host_reset(sc);

 		if (bus_width)
 			dwmmc_bus_width(sc, bus_width);
 		if (bus_freq)
 			dwmmc_bus_clock(sc, bus_freq, bus_timing);
 		break;
 	}

 	return config_activate_children(self, act);

Notes:
  - sc->sc_vmmc is 0 when no vmmc-supply is in DT. The regulator_disable
    call is skipped (guarded above); sc_vdd = 0 still triggers
    bus_power to run pwrseq_pre/post on the next attach, which is the
    minimum behaviour the original error-60 fix delivered.
  - On boards that mark the bus non-removable (SMC_CAPS_NONREMOVABLE),
    the sdmmc layer will not force-detach on suspend and therefore
    will not call bus_power on resume; for those boards an explicit
    pwrseq call would still be needed. DM250 doesn't take that path
    (dwmmc.c does not honour DT non-removable today), so the current
    setup is consistent.
  - The retained dwmmc_pwrseq_pre / post functions (around lines
    1310-1380 of dwmmc.c) are unchanged; they continue to be invoked
    from dwmmc_bus_power on every 0 -> on vdd transition.
